	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: RF shield on NES really necessary?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">17daysolderthannes wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">P.P.S. I noticed that after the system was unplugged, if I pushed the power button it would flash the LED for a split second, is this because it isn't grounding due to the absence of the RF shield or is it just a capacitor discharging somewhere?</div>
<br />That's normal, happens all the time to me.
<br />
<br />About the RF-shield, it pretty much speaks for itself.
<br />It protects your video output from picking up 'unwanted cosmic signals', and makes your video output cleaner (As far as I know).
<br />
<br />What a coincidence that you also were changing the 72-pin of your NES.
<br />My NES on the other hand is now declared broken.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
